.docname {Dashboard: Digital Twin Analytics}
.include {docs}

When you switch the Dashboard from the default "List" view to the "Graph" view, you access the visual analytics engine. This section provides a deeper look into historical trends and simulated data for your selected building.

---

## The Sensor View (Graphs)

The Sensor View transforms raw data into easy-to-read charts, helping administrators identify patterns over time. The dashboard focuses on two primary data streams:

*   **Occupancy (People Count) Graph:** This graph visualizes the number of people inside the selected spaces. It helps administrators understand traffic flow, peak usage hours, and whether rooms consistently hit their maximum capacity thresholds.
*   **Temperature Graph:** This graph tracks the climate of the selected rooms. By monitoring temperature trends against maximum thresholds, administrators can ensure student comfort and HVAC efficiency.

**Historical Data Tracking:**
The graphs don't just show real-time numbers; they aggregate historical data points over specific time ranges. The system calculates the average, maximum, and minimum values for both people count and temperature, allowing you to review past events and trends.

Both charts are driven by data aggregated from the sensor database. They update automatically according to the selected time range.

> 💡 When **Sum** aggregation is selected, only the Occupancy chart is shown and it expands to full width, since summing temperatures across rooms is not meaningful.

---

## ⏱️ Time Range

Use the **Range** buttons in the top-right area to control how far back in time the charts look:

| Range | What it shows |
| :--- | :--- |
| **1D** | The last 24 hours, broken down hour by hour. |
| **1W** | The last 7 days, broken down day by day. |
| **1M** | The last 30 days, broken down day by day. |

Switching the range causes the charts to immediately reload with the appropriate data resolution. Points with no sensor data for a given hour or day appear as zero.

---

## 🔢 Data Aggregation Mode

Because a building has many rooms, the charts aggregate all room readings into a single value per time slot. Use the **Data** buttons to choose how that aggregation is calculated:

| Mode | What it means |
| :--- | :--- |
| **avg** | The average value across all rooms in that time slot. Useful for understanding the typical state of the building. |
| **sum** | The total across all rooms. Most useful for people count — shows the total number of people in the entire building at each point in time. |
| **min** | The lowest reading recorded in that time slot. Useful for spotting unusually cold rooms. |
| **max** | The highest reading recorded in that time slot. Most useful for temperature — quickly spots the hottest room. |

---

## 🤖 Sensor Simulation

CrowdVision includes a built-in Simulator feature. This is incredibly useful for testing the system, demonstrating the platform, or simulating emergency crowding scenarios without needing active, physical sensors.

.box type:{note}
    The simulator is a separate service that runs independently from the main application. Before using the simulation controls, an administrator or developer must start the simulator container on their machine and provide you with its URL. See the section below for details.

### Configuring the Simulator URL

1. Click the **gear icon** (⚙) next to the simulator button.
2. A modal will appear asking for the **Simulator URL** — this is the address where the simulator service is running (e.g., `http://localhost:3001`).
3. Enter the URL and click **Save**. The dashboard remembers this URL, so you only need to enter it once per browser.

### Starting and Stopping Simulation

Once the URL is configured:

1. Click the **Start simulator** button. It turns green with an animated dot when the simulator is active.
2. The simulator will begin sending synthetic people count and temperature readings to the sensor API every 10 seconds for the currently selected building and all its rooms.
3. After a few seconds, the charts will begin showing data as readings accumulate. The `1D` range with `avg` mode is the best view to see incoming data appear in real time.
4. To stop, click the button again (now labelled **Stop simulator**). Data transmission halts and the button returns to its inactive state.

.box type:{note}
    The simulator status shown in the button is automatically checked whenever you switch buildings. If you start the simulator for Building A and then switch to Building B, the button will show the correct inactive state for Building B — the simulator is still running for Building A in the background.

### What the Simulator Generates

The simulator creates random but realistic readings within the following ranges for each room in the selected building, every 10 seconds:

| Metric | Range |
| :--- | :--- |
| People count | 0 to 50 occupants |
| Temperature | 18.0°C to 30.0°C |

Each room in the building receives its own independent reading per tick.

---

## 🔔 Notifications from Sensor Data

As sensor data flows in — whether from the simulator or real IoT devices — CrowdVision continuously evaluates each reading against the room's configured thresholds. If a room exceeds its capacity or surpasses its maximum temperature setting:

* The **Notification Bell** in the top navigation bar turns red and displays a counter.
* A **toast alert** slides onto the screen with the details of the breach.
* If you have enabled browser push notifications, an alert will be delivered even when the dashboard is not open.

This means you do not need to watch the charts to stay informed — the system watches for you.
